    {
      "dimension": "philosophy_depth",
      "score": 6,
      "finding": "The six guiding principles are broadly relevant but read as generic sales platitudes rather than SDR-specific rules of engagement tied to Story Portal use cases.",
      "example_rewrite": "Replace “Activity Creates Results” with “Account-Based Personalization: Each outreach includes 3 research-driven points about the prospect’s festival or community initiative to boost reply rates.”"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "anti_pattern_quality",
      "score": 2,
      "finding": "There is no dedicated anti-patterns section for the SDR role. Common SDR pitfalls (e.g., blasting generic emails, skipping CRM updates) are not called out.",
      "example_rewrite": "### Anti-Patterns\n1. Generic Blasts: Sending mass emails without personalization—dilutes brand and lowers response rates.\n2. Qualification Avoidance: Not asking open-ended questions—leads remain unvalidated and waste AE time.\n3. CRM Neglect: Failing to log calls and notes immediately—creates data gaps and misaligns downstream teams.\n4. Sequence Overload: Over-automating follow-ups without human review—risks spamming high-value targets."
    }
  ],
  "top_improvement": "Add a role-specific Anti-Patterns section with 3–5 common SDR missteps and mitigation examples."
}

```json
{
  "role": "sales-development-rep",
  "department": "sales",
  "scores": {
    "philosophy_depth": 2,
    "handoff_specificity": 4,
    "anti_pattern_quality": 1,
    "ai_deployment_clarity": 5,
    "story_portal_relevance": 5
  },
  "findings": [
    {
      "dimension": "philosophy_depth",
      "score": 2,
      "finding": "All 6 principles are universal sales clichés that could appear in any SDR job description from 2005. 'Activity Creates Results,' 'Quality Over Quantity,' 'Persistence Pays' — these are motivational poster slogans, not operational principles. None reference Story Portal's mission context, the specific prospect segments (festival organizers, sponsors), or the Hybrid human/AI division of labor. The Meaning column adds nothing — 'Volume matters' explains nothing about how this SDR should behave differently than any other SDR.",
      "example_rewrite": "| **Mission-Led Prospecting** | Story Portal sells to festival organizers and arts communities motivated by impact, not features — lead every sequence with the empathy mission before platform capability | **Qualify for Values Fit First** | A prospect who books a meeting but misaligns with community-building goals wastes AE time; disqualify early on mission alignment, not just budget | **AI Handles Volume, Human Handles Trust** | Sequence execution and enrichment are Agent tasks; rapport, objection handling, and discovery are always Human tasks — never let AI conduct a qualifying conversation | **Inbound Speed is a Conversion Variable** | Festival organizers evaluate multiple platforms simultaneously; a 5-minute inbound response window outperforms a 2-hour response by measurable pipeline conversion | **Disqualification is a Deliverable** | A well-documented disqualified lead with clear reason codes is as valuable as a booked meeting — it protects AE capacity and improves targeting data | **Segment Sequencing Over Generic Cadences** | Festival Organizers, Brand Sponsors, and Arts Organizations require distinct sequence logic — one universal cadence is a signal of poor ICP discipline |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "handoff_specificity",
      "score": 4,
      "finding": "Handoff tables name roles but artifacts are vague labels, not actual documents. 'Inbound leads' from Marketing, 'Prospect intelligence' from Sales Research, 'Qualified meetings' to Account Executive — none of these specify format, required fields, or what constitutes a complete artifact. The AE briefing is the most critical handoff in the SDR workflow and it receives no specification whatsoever. 'Activity data' delivered to Sales Ops could mean anything. There are no STOP checkpoints embedded in handoffs — no moment where a human must approve before the next stage begins.",
      "example_rewrite": "| Delivers To | Artifact | Required Fields | STOP Condition | | Account Executive | AE Meeting Brief (CRM opportunity record + 1-page brief doc) | Prospect name, title, company, ICP fit score, pain statement, budget signal, decision-maker confirmed Y/N, meeting agenda, SDR notes | STOP: AE must acknowledge brief receipt before meeting proceeds | | Sales Ops | Weekly Activity Report (CRM export .csv) | Calls attempted, emails sent, LinkedIn touches, meetings booked, disqualified count with reason codes, sequence performance by segment | STOP: Sales Ops flags anomalies before next week's targets are set | | Sales Director | Pipeline Contribution Report | Meetings booked vs. quota, qualification rate, top-performing sequence by segment, blockers requiring strategy input | STOP: Director approves approach adjustments before SDR changes targeting |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "anti_pattern_quality",
      "score": 1,
      "finding": "There is no Anti-Patterns section in this role file at all. The template standard explicitly requires 3-5 role-specific anti-patterns. The DO/DON'T boundary list in the Boundaries section is not a substitute — those are ownership rules, not behavioral failure modes. The absence of anti-patterns is a critical omission for a Hybrid role where the AI/human boundary is especially prone to failure (e.g., AI conducting qualifying conversations it shouldn't, or SDR letting sequences run without human review of replies).",
      "example_rewrite": "## Anti-Patterns\n\n| Anti-Pattern | What It Looks Like | Why It Fails |\n|---|---|---|\n| **AI Qualifying Conversations** | Agent responds to a prospect reply with discovery questions instead of flagging for human takeover | Damages trust with mission-driven prospects; Story Portal's community-oriented buyers detect automated discovery immediately and disengage |\n| **Booking Meetings Without Values Fit Check** | SDR hits meeting quota by booking any interested prospect regardless of mission alignment | AE pipeline fills with prospects who churn at demo stage; wastes AE capacity on non-ICP accounts |\n| **Generic Sequences Across All Segments** | Running Festival Organizers and Brand Sponsors through identical email cadences | Conversion rates collapse; festival organizers respond to impact framing, sponsors respond to audience data — conflating them signals low research quality |\n| **Skipping AE Brief to Hit Speed Metrics** | Handing off a meeting with only a calendar invite and no brief document | AE walks into discovery blind; prospect repeats context already shared with SDR; damages buyer confidence in the company |\n| **Treating Disqualification as Failure** | SDR avoids disqualifying borderline prospects to protect activity numbers | Inflates pipeline metrics; creates false revenue forecasts; Sales Director loses trust in SDR-sourced pipeline quality |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "ai_deployment_clarity",
      "score": 5,
      "finding": "The Iteration Protocol exists but is too abstract to operationalize. The loop says 'Execute prospecting activities' then 'STOP → Report on qualified meetings' but gives no criteria for when to STOP — after how many touches? After a reply is received? The AI/human split in the Deployment Notes section lists tasks correctly but provides no decision tree for when the Agent must hand off to Human mid-workflow. The Context Requirements section is unfilled placeholders ('[Context item 1]') and the Required Skills table is empty — an AI agent loading this role cannot determine what context files to load. Browser Capabilities list 'Phone conversations' which is not an actual browser capability, creating confusion about what the agent can actually execute.",
      "example_rewrite": "### Iteration Protocol\n\n```\nLOOP (Agent executes):\n  1. Pull target list from Sales Ops (ICP target list v[current].csv)\n  2. Enrich prospects via LinkedIn Sales Navigator — flag any missing title/company/contact info\n  3. Enqueue into sequence by segment (Festival Organizer / Sponsor / Arts Org)\n  4. Execute sequence steps: send emails, log LinkedIn touches, log call attempts in CRM\n  5. STOP TRIGGER: Any prospect replies to outreach → HALT automation on that contact\n  6. WAIT: Flag reply for Human SDR review within 15 minutes\n  7. Human SDR takes over: conducts live conversation, qualifies, books or disqualifies\n  8. Human SDR logs outcome in CRM; updates qualification field\n  9. IF meeting booked → Agent generates AE Brief draft for Human SDR review\n  10. Human SDR reviews and submits brief → handoff complete\n  11. IF human says STOP or PAUSE → Agent halts all active sequences immediately\n  12. REPEAT from step 1 on next prospecting cycle\n```\n\n### Required Context\n- [ ] icp-profiles.md — Festival Organizer, Brand Sponsor, Arts Organization definitions\n- [ ] sequence-library.md — Approved sequences by segment\n- [ ] qualification-criteria.md — BANT + values-fit scoring rubric\n- [ ] ae-brief-template.md — Required fields for meeting handoff"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "story_portal_relevance",
      "score": 5,
      "finding": "The Story Portal appendix names the right segments and themes but provides no actionable specificity. 'Mission alignment' and 'Impact focus' as approaches tell the SDR nothing about what to actually say or do differently. The Messaging Themes table lists themes ('Empathy mission,' 'Community building') without connecting them to sequence steps, call openers, or objection responses. The priorities table ranks activity but gives no quota numbers, target account counts, or segment ratios. A new SDR reading this appendix would know Story Portal is purpose-driven but could not write a single outreach email or qualify a single call differently than they would for any other company.",
      "example_rewrite": "### Story Portal SDR Playbook\n\n| Segment | First-Touch Angle | Qualifying Question | Disqualify If |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Festival Organizers | 'Story Portal was built around festival communities — we help organizers capture and share attendee stories across the event lifecycle. Are you currently doing anything to preserve the stories from [Festival Name]?' | 'How important is community storytelling to your festival's identity and sponsorship pitch?' | They view storytelling as marketing only, not community value |\n| Brand Sponsors | 'Brands on Story Portal reach festival audiences through authentic community stories rather than ad placements — our sponsor partners average [X]% higher engagement than traditional festival sponsorship. Is authentic audience connection a priority for your current festival partnerships?' | 'What does meaningful community engagement look like for your sponsorship goals?' | Budget under $[threshold] or no festival sponsorship program |\n| Arts Organizations | 'Story Portal partners with arts organizations to digitally preserve and share the stories behind their work and audiences. Are you doing anything to capture the stories your programming creates?' | 'Is digital storytelling or community archiving on your roadmap for this year?' | No community engagement program or digital presence |\n\n**SDR Targets (Story Portal):** 15 meetings/month — 8 Festival Organizer, 4 Brand Sponsor, 3 Arts Organization"
    }
  ],
  "top_improvement": "Add a complete Anti-Patterns section immediately — this is the only critical template section entirely absent from the file. A Hybrid role with AI sequence execution and human qualification is precisely where behavioral failure modes cause the most damage (AI conducting conversations it should not, meetings booked without values-fit checks, AE briefs skipped under activity pressure). Without anti-patterns, every AI agent and human SDR operating this role has no guardrails against the highest-probability failure modes specific to Story Portal's mission-driven sales context."
}
```
